<exercise>
<!-- source latex = 'If ab is 1 mod n and c is not zero mod n, then ac is nonzero mod n.tex' -->
<!-- converted on 03/03/2022 at 12:05 -->
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>n\in\mathbb{N}</m>, <m>n\geq 2</m>, and <m>a,b\in\mathbb{Z}</m>. Prove
that if <m>ab\equiv 1 \pmod{n}</m>, then
<m>\forall c\in \mathbb{Z}, c\not\equiv 0\pmod{n}</m> we have
<m>ac\not\equiv 0\pmod{n}</m>.
</p>
</statement>
<solution>

<proof><p>
Let <m>a,b\in \mathbb{Z}</m> and <m>n\geq 2</m>. By way of contradiction, suppose that there exists an integer <m>c\not\equiv 0 \pmod{n}</m> such that we have both
<md>
<mrow>
    ab \amp \equiv 1 \pmod{n}  \amp  \text{and} \tag{1}
</mrow><mrow>
    ac \amp \equiv 0\pmod{n}.  \amp  \tag{2}
</mrow>
</md>
</p>
<p>
We consider <m>abc \pmod{n}</m>. On the one hand, we use statement (1) to see that
<me>(ab)c \equiv c \pmod{n}. \tag{3} </me>
On the other hand, we use expression (2) to see
<me>(ac)b \equiv 0(b) \equiv 0 \pmod{n}. \tag{4}</me>
Therefore, combining statements (3) and (4) we obtain
<me>c \equiv abc \equiv 0 \pmod{n}.</me>
This contradicts the assumption that <m>c\not\equiv 0 \pmod{n}</m>.
</p></proof>

</solution>
</exercise>